ves in war zones and established their position as the expert at the bedside. Yet, despite the acknowledgement of nurses' vital role in the medical service, their position was gendered. As the women of Britain were returned to the home post-war, it was the military nurses' womanhood that stymied their considerable skills from being transferred to the new welfare state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory (General). 0aHistory. 0aMedicine (General). 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aGender boundaries.  aNurses' presence.  aNursing work.  aPersonal testimon.  aProfessional boundaries.  aSecond World War.  aWomen's space.  aWomen's war work.1 aBrooks, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526147257zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526147257zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526147257/original  a978-3-11-128277-0 Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA